# Validation & Security Patterns

## Zod Schemas
- Live in `src/node/lib/validation/{domain}.ts`
- Export a `{domain}Schemas` object, re-export from `index.ts`
- Use `jsonObject` helper for arbitrary JSON fields (has depth + size limits)
- Bound arrays: `.array(z.string().max(100)).max(20)` — always set max length + element length
- Use `.nullable()` for fields that can be null from external providers

## Input Flow
```
REST:    parseBody(await c.req.text(), schema) → sanitizeObject(validated) → DB write
GraphQL: schema.parse(input)                   → sanitizeObject(validated) → DB write
```
Never skip steps. `sanitizeObject` HTML-escapes strings and validates URLs on `RAW_STRING_KEYS`.
`parseBody` takes the raw body string (not a Lambda event).

## Security Checklist for New Endpoints
- [ ] Zod schema validates all input fields with appropriate constraints
- [ ] `sanitizeObject()` applied before any DB write
- [ ] Auth: `requireAuth()` (applied in `routes/index.ts`) protects the route; claims via `c.get("claims")`. GraphQL `/v1/graphql` is mounted behind the same `requireAuth()`.
- [ ] Null guard: check DB results before returning (`if (!result) throw ...`)
- [ ] Audit: `logAudit()` called on all mutations
- [ ] Transactions: multi-step writes wrapped in `db.transaction()`
- [ ] File uploads: validate magic bytes, content-type/extension match, size limit (see `lib/media.ts`)

## Error Handling
- REST: `throw Errors.NotFound("User")` — middleware formats the response
- GraphQL: `throw new GraphQLError("msg", { extensions: { code: "NOT_FOUND" } })`
- Never return raw error details in production — `formatError` masks non-safe codes
- Safe GraphQL codes: BAD_USER_INPUT, GRAPHQL_VALIDATION_FAILED, GRAPHQL_PARSE_FAILED, FORBIDDEN, UNAUTHENTICATED, NOT_FOUND, CONFLICT

## CORS
- Dynamic origin matching via `CORS_EXACT_ORIGINS`, `CORS_PARENT_DOMAINS`, `CORS_DOMAIN_PATTERNS` (`wrangler.toml [vars]`)
- HTTPS enforced for non-localhost origins
- The app-level `corsAndSecurityHeaders()` middleware (`lib/hono/middleware.ts`) answers OPTIONS preflight and decorates every response; `app.ts` `onError` re-applies the same CORS + security headers to error responses. Routes never set CORS themselves.
